Key findings: the real cross-module graph is a single per-player event bus chain, not direct module calls. The strongest proven correlations are `Bag -> {Task, Achievement, Equipment}` via `item.added`, then `Task -> Achievement`, `Equipment -> Achievement`, and finally `{Achievement, SignIn} -> Mail`. Every handler filters on `playerID`, so the bus is globally shared but logically partitioned per player.

The highest-risk hypotheses are the business-layer negative remove in [internal/bag/bag.go](/mnt/d/assistant/integration-testing-guide/ai-integration-test-demo/internal/bag/bag.go:45), the reward dead-end in [internal/mail/mail.go](/mnt/d/assistant/integration-testing-guide/ai-integration-test-demo/internal/mail/mail.go:79), and bag/equipment divergence in [internal/equipment/equipment.go](/mnt/d/assistant/integration-testing-guide/ai-integration-test-demo/internal/equipment/equipment.go:42). Static-only note: I did not run the system; these are source-backed hypotheses. No files changed. Remaining risk is that some low-confidence defects, especially B7, may reflect intentional demo design rather than accidental behavior.
